In this part of the codebase we have assessor classes that assess which items, in several long lists of items, are available for use given the currently available prerequisites. The idea of the reverse brute tester is to test all prerequisites, for every item, by enabling all prerequisites and then toggling off one prerequisites at a time. For each toggled prerequisites, one then has to iterate over all the items and see which items remain available. For any item that is now unavailable, the prerequisite gets marked as relevant for that item. It is very important to know that there several different types of prerequisites, as well as several different types of items. If the total number of items is I, and the total number of prerequisites is P, then the complexity of the test function is PI. 

Currently items have a tech prerequisite, and between 0 and 4 additional prerequisites that may be of any type, except for tech. The other prerequisite types are flags, buildings, and resources. The prerequisites are logged as simple numbers, and therefore need an additional indicator of type. 

After we have brute-forced the prerequisites, the tester needs to read to actual game data, and make sure for each item the name of each logged prerequisite appears in the data line. 
